<br>
Shamen Kite.<br>
<br>
Enchanters Kite.<br>
<br>
Mages can Kite, so can Necros(though most do not).<br>
<br>
Is it really Kiting? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=faynedethe>Fayne Dethe</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 1:10:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27062.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What makes Druids &quot;Over Balanced&quot; prior to 50?</span><hr size=1>   Supposedly its the ability to solo reds, but spells are resisted on reds just like any other caster class, unlike melee who can beat on reds when being powerleveled or whatever.  Also, pre-50 necros and shamans can root/dot far better than druids can (shamans can slow/dot/melee with pet, and necros can fear kite solo).  I also found my magician can solo far more effectively than my druid used to be able to (not touching on post 50 life ;p).   Oh and if people complain about classes pre-35 give me a break.  Melee classes can get weapons like centi long-sword for dirt-cheap and totally own low levels while casters are still stuck with their underpowered low level spells.  Add in a fungi tunic and it gets quite ridiculous (albiet, fungi are more expensive now ;p).<br>
<br>
Opps, forgot to mention quad-kiting.  That wasnt even done pre-kunark, it came about a month or so after Kunark came into existence when I was around 51 ;p.  Even then, the first truly effective quad-kite spell is at 49 for druids, but leveling that way is still slow cause of 10+ minute downtime, no significant mana regen spells till 60, and very few places to quadkite that are all over-crowded (CS, raptors post 50).   <p>Fayne Dethe<BR> 
Level 60 Druid of Xegony<BR>
Havenlight</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=faynedethe>Fayne Dethe</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0> at: 4/9/02 1:18:00 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uvenytir.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Venytir</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 2:31:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27062.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> .</span><hr size=1> HAHAH<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Mage's can kite<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I think that, coming from a PVP perspective, the druid is so versitile in PVP that they can kill almost everyone in almost every situation. (Tanks are a tough one in dungeons, but a well played druid is better off then a wizard or an enchanter.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> List of Problems</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
1. Winged Death - This is too strong. Too fast. Too easy to cast and then bail.<br>
2. No balance of abilities - Every class is dependent on others for support. A druid doesn't have nearly as many limitations (it can heal, port, nuke, buff and dot).<br>
3. Unkillable - A well played druid is like a well played Pally, unkillable.<br>
4. Common - There are more druids then needed in every single situation thinkable.<br>
5. Quad-kiting - Nuff Said.. like wizards, it's a really nice thing to have.<br>
<br>
These are all major reasons why druids are so disliked. Druids aren't balanced because they can do everything. They step on other classes toes in almost everything but pets. Yet they still manage to whine about stuff (not that it is unwarrented, just that it is irritating). <br>
<br>
As a mage, I am faced with the same plight you are, lack of a defined role post-50. Pre-50, you are a god-class. You can easily solo (like a necromancer), plus you can port, plus you can group better then most, plus you have the most utility pre-50 of any class (bards are iffy, but I still think ports &gt; *). In reality, you have absolutely nothing wrong. No limitations. That's the &quot;over-balanced&quot; part. You aren't restrained by any problems. (excluding of course, your leather armor) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=lunariel>lunariel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 2:33:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27062.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What makes Druids &quot;Over Balanced&quot; prior to 50?</span><hr size=1> From what I've read of the history of the game, Druids were the most powerful 2 years ago, especially soloing. Then VI rooted us to let the other classes catch up. VI even stated that they wanted to reduce the popularity of Druids. Now over half the classes can solo better (overall DPS) than us, but people are still a bit slow and haven't realized this yet. Also a lot of people wants to have a class to hate. Druids were easy targets back then and old habits die hard.<br>
<br>
Druids are perhaps still the easiest class to play for casual soloers, so there are still a lot of us around. But it's no longer a power class, others have taken that spot. Unfortunately the high end raid scene was fleshed out during these last 2 years which left the Druids near the bottom of list. Only flawed game design for pets saved us from ending up last.<br>
<br>
Druids are still rooted. Luclin didn't bring anything new and Wolf Form is still KoS. But since 'The Vision' is now dead and buried, there is a chance that the new dev team might drop the root and settle with a snare instead. <br>
<br>
Lunariel<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ustormhaven.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stormhaven</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 3:09:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27062.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://web2.airmail.net/naomi/amalgam/forum/stormhaven.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Back in the ancient times of pre-Kunark...  :/<br>
Except for very few points at various pre-hell-level-don't-have-my-new-heal-yet stages, the druid was very well balanced.  The druid heals were good enough to put you into a 50's main healer position, and you had some of the better DD's in the game (speaking of pure dmg, not mana ratio).<br>
<br>
When you added Kunark into the mix, things went haywire.  1500HP was no longer a lot of hit points.  Our DD's were still nice, but our DoT's are what really caught us up.  Healing suffered a lot.  We could no longer be very good main healers unless you planned at being around 20% mana the whole time you're in a single group.  You'd be lucky if you had the WIS/Mana to keep a warrior alive in Sebilis.  More than likely, the only reason you were being invited into groups was for your evac abilities.  (Remember, chloroblast and Nature's Touch weren't added until later).  Regrowth of the Grove was nice, but it probably wasn't going to save your butt from a quad 100pt attack.<br>
<br>
With Velious we really started to suffer.  Our new spells were neat, but all of our buffs were mostly useless.  Girdle of Tunare was nothing compared to Focus.  Why take a druid with PotG when you had a cleric with Aego?  Yes, the mana regen was nice, but that's not going to do a whole lot for your tank.  Our DS was never used with a mage around.  We had self-mana recovery spells now, but too bad they're all outdoors only, and probably made you KoS to 90% of the population.<br>
<br>
Now we're at Luclin and our buffs are pretty much completely useless.  Some of the casting classes might still like to get a PoTG now and then, but trying to keep PoTG with Marzin is annoying.  Plus, since clerics now have Blessed Armor of the Risen, they don't even need PoTG.  Our DS is still second class, our new SoW breaks DMF, Nature's Recovery is pretty much a single-target buff only; which is very underpowered, and our indoor self-mana regen spell seems to drop only on one mob, 2% of the time.<br>
<br>
Pre-Kunark, and a little bit after Kunark's release, we were the class to be.  We could level faster than most other classes, we could heal, damage, buff, port, manaregen, the whole she-bang.  Quad-kiting wasn't around as much, we didn't really have the mana ratio for it, and not many locations existed.  Why were we considered &quot;over-powered&quot;?  It was because of our ability to solo *and* our ability to group.  Can't find a group in Guk?  Go out to solo guards, giants, Cyclopes, etc.  The fact was, we could get xp in both dungeons with groups and solo.  Not only could we do it, we could do it well.<br>
<br>
Now? <br>
<br>
Now we work well solo, and we work as a good &quot;filler&quot; in a group.  You can still solo your way to level 60 and 2340983 AA points (boring as it is), but you're by no means the fastest leveler anymore.  In raids you're the fill CB heal on the main tank in between CH's.  If you're lucky, you'll get to debuff fire resist on some mob.<br>
<br>
That's all immaterial though.  <br>
<br>
What makes other classes &quot;think&quot; we're overpowered? <br>
That's easy.<br>
It's druids.<br>
<br>
Druids were the ones who were PL'd to level 50 in 4 days played.  Druids were some of the first lvl 60's.  Druids were the ones to get their epic made easier.  Druids were the ones who got new heals to &quot;balance&quot; them.<br>
<br>
All the while, druids were the ones who would complain about being underpowered, then in the same breath tell you how they quad-kite raptors for xp in TD.  The &quot;image&quot; of the druid as being overpowered is that which is perpetuated by the druid and accepted by the rest of the classes.  The &quot;image&quot; of the druid is the one being shown by the ass in Cobalt Scar quad kiting 4 out of the 20 total wyverns spawned, training other groups when Yvolcarn or Azuredrake spawns.  The &quot;image&quot; of the druid is the one shown to others as a level 60 camping a level 40 mob to twink their lower level character instead of giving the camp to a group who could get xp there.<br>
<br>
Druids are their own worst enemy, and our reputation precedes us.   <p><body link="#FFFFFF" vlink="#CCCCCC">

