I don't think PVP = PVE, cause it doesn't. But from my perspective, that's why they are overpowered in PVP and PVE. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usorrun.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sorrun</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 5:04:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27062.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What makes Druids &quot;Over Balanced&quot; prior to 50?</span><hr size=1> The simple answer to your question, I think, is "versitility".  There is a lot more power in that one ability then many druids realize or want to admit.<br>
<br>
The more complicated answer is that I dont think the concept of having to "pay" for past advantages is reasonable.  It really makes no sense.  What I do think is reasonable is that druids of all levels have to accept that with verstility comes lack of specialized skills.  You cant have it both ways although it is very obvious that several high level druids around here want exactly that now that they are 60 and the need for versatitly isnt near as great as it was from 1-55 (although you can be sure they took full advantage of that for 55 levels).  If anything, it is an interesting, even ironic twist.<br>
<br>
It seems to me that raids are all about efficency and that requires specialzed skills to get things accomplished with the least amount of grief.  This goes against most of what it means to be a druid.  <br>
<br>
Is there room for improvement?  Sure.. but there isnt much room before you start unbalancing other classes and more or less infringing on specialized skills.  Combine even one specialzed skill with an inheirent versatility and you get one overpowered class.  I think I saw that recipe in a magazine once.  :)<br>
<br>
